ðŸ§© 1. Introduction to HTML

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the structure of a webpage.
It tells the browser what each part of the page is â€” like headings, paragraphs, images, or links.

ðŸ“˜ Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>My First Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Welcome!</h1>
    <p>This is my first webpage using HTML.</p>
  </body>
</html>
Every HTML page has a fixed structure:

Part	Purpose
<!DOCTYPE html>	Declares HTML5 version.
<html>	Root element (wraps all content).
<head>	Contains metadata (title, CSS links, etc).
<body>	Visible content (text, images, etc).

ðŸ“˜ Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Document Structure</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h2>Page Content Goes Here</h2>
  </body>
</html>

3. HTML Elements and Tags

Tag: keyword inside < > that defines an element.

Element: opening tag + content + closing tag.

ðŸ“˜ Example:

<p>Hello World!</p>


Here:

<p> = opening tag

</p> = closing tag

"Hello World!" = content
âœ… Together they form an HTML element.

Some tags are self-closing (no closing tag):

<img src="photo.jpg" alt="My Photo">
<br>
<hr>

4. Attributes and Values

Attributes give extra information about elements.
They are always written in the opening tag.

ðŸ“˜ Example:

<a href="https://www.google.com" target="_blank">Visit Google</a>
<img src="car.jpg" alt="Red Car" width="300">


href â†’ link address

target="_blank" â†’ open in new tab

src â†’ image source

alt â†’ alternate text if image fails

width â†’ control size

ðŸ§  Syntax rule:
attribute="value"

ðŸ’¬ 5. Comments in HTML

Comments are used to explain code.
They are not shown in the browser.

ðŸ“˜ Example:

<!-- This is a comment -->
<p>This text will appear.</p>
